# tccloud - A Python Client for TeraChem Cloud

`tccloud` is a python package that provides an easy interface to the TeraChem Cloud web service. All input and output data structures are based on the [QCSchema](https://molssi-qc-schema.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html#) specification designed by [The Molecular Sciences Software Institute](https://molssi.org) as implemented in their [QCElemental](http://docs.qcarchive.molssi.org/projects/QCElemental/en/stable/) package. This enables common and well defined input/output data structures to be used to power a whole suite of Quantum Chemistry packages.

## Basic Usage

`tccloud` stands on the shoulders of giants. The `AtomicInput`, `Molecule`, `Model`, and `AtomicResult` models used throughout the package come directly from [QCElemental](http://docs.qcarchive.molssi.org/projects/QCElemental/en/stable/). They are included in `tccloud.models` for your convenience.

```python
from tccloud.models import AtomicInput, Molecule, Model
from tccloud import TCClient

# Instantiate a client
client = TCClient()
client.configure() # only required once the first time you ever use the client

# Instantiate your molecule of interest
# http://docs.qcarchive.molssi.org/en/latest/basic_examples/QCElemental.html#Molecule-Parsing-and-Models
# http://docs.qcarchive.molssi.org/projects/QCElemental/en/stable/model_molecule.html
water = Molecule.from_data("pubchem:water")
# Create your model
model = Model(method="B3LYP", basis="6-31g")
# Specify driver: energy, gradient, hessian, or property
driver = "energy"
# Create AtomicInput
# http://docs.qcarchive.molssi.org/projects/QCElemental/en/stable/model_result.html
atomic_input = AtomicInput(molecule=water, model=model, driver=driver)
# Compute result
future_result = client.compute(atomic_input, engine="psi4") # returns FutureResult object
# .get() blocks until result is available, returns AtomicResult object
# http://docs.qcarchive.molssi.org/projects/QCElemental/en/stable/model_result.html
result = future_result.get()
```

## Development

Install package with development and testing dependencies.

```sh
flit install
```

